Hello, sorry for yet another question  <!-- s:oops: --><img src="{SMILIES_PATH}/icon_redface.gif" alt=":oops:" title="Embarassed" /><!-- s:oops: --> 

What I want to code now is:


IF ( Something = True AND Somethingelse = TRUE ) {
  dosomething
}

Is there an &quot;AND&quot; operator I can use for this?  I've mostly been using the code interface rather than the raw code screen, and can't see a way of adding an AND.

Or do I need to use nested IFs?

IF ( Something = True) {
  IF ( Somethingelse = True) {
    do something
  }
}

psymann

Yes, it's called &quot;and&quot; <!-- s:) --><img src="{SMILIES_PATH}/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><!-- s:) -->

What you typed should probably work. It's not in the interface since basically it's part of an expression.

[code:2c4m7h72]IF ( Something and Somethingelse) {
 dosomething
}[/code:2c4m7h72]

To be honest, you *can* do it with nested if's if you want... it's up to you. <!-- s:) --><img src="{SMILIES_PATH}/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><!-- s:) --> 

There's also &quot;or&quot; and &quot;not&quot;.

[code:3m0vw2ql]if ((a or b) and not c) {
&#46;&#46;&#46;
}[/code:3m0vw2ql]

It's the same if you wanted to check &quot;x &gt; 1&quot; or &quot;x + y &lt;&gt; z&quot;. You'd have to type it in. So, yes... expressions. <!-- s:) --><img src="{SMILIES_PATH}/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><!-- s:) -->
